13 CODIFY LIMITS OF EXISTING RIGHTS-OF-WAY AND EASEMENTS
14 MAINTAINED BY THE DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION TO PROVIDE
15 CLARITY AND CONSISTENCY FOR PERSONS IMPACTED BY PREVIOUS
16 PROPERTY TRANSACTIONS THAT WERE NOT DOCUMENTED OR RECORDED
17 IN ACCORDANCE WITH CURRENT REQUIREMENTS
18 SECTION 14.(a) Article 2A of Chapter 136 of the General Statutes is amended by
19 adding a new section to read:
20 "§ 136-44.18. Define boundaries of certain rights-of-way and easements.
21 (a) Right-of-Way Boundaries. – Notwithstanding any provision of law to the contrary,
22 for any roadway for which the Department has responsibility for maintenance, but there is no
23 instrument of conveyance describing the boundaries of the right-of-way, the boundary of the
24 right-of-way shall be defined according to the typical maintenance limits that are Department
25 practice.
26 (b) Easement Boundaries. – Notwithstanding any provision of law to the contrary, for
27 any roadway for which the Department has responsibility for maintenance, but there is no
28 instrument of conveyance describing the boundaries of the easement, the boundary of the
29 easement shall be defined according to the typical maintenance limits that are Department
30 practice.
31 (c) Conditions Imposed on Developers. – If the Department, as a condition of granting a
32 permit, requires a developer to construct offsite improvements, and by constructing offsite
33 improvements there is a need for the developer to acquire a right-of-way or easement and the
34 developer is unable to do so, the Department shall coordinate with the developer to revise the
35 development or development access such that no additional right-of-way or easement is needed.
36 The Department shall comply with the requirement set forth in this subsection within a reasonable
37 amount of time after the developer provides evidence to the Department that the developer made
38 a good-faith effort to acquire the required right-of-way or easement. For purposes of this
39 subsection, the term "good faith effort" includes providing a copy of a certified letter to all
40 affected property owners and all responses received from those property owners.
41 (d) Construction. – Nothing in this section shall be construed as allowing (i) the
42 Department to require a Hold Harmless declaration from a developer or (ii) the Department to
43 take any action that would constitute a taking of property in violation of the Constitution of this
44 State or of the United States."
45 SECTION 14.(b) By October 1, 2025, the Department of Transportation shall submit
46 a report to the Joint Legislative Transportation Oversight Committee (i) describing the
47 maintenance limits used by the Department in G.S. 136-44.18, as enacted by subsection (a) of
48 this section, and (ii) recommending any additional legislative changes that may further aid in
49 defining the boundaries of rights-of-way and easements subject to G.S. 136-44.18.
