8 INCREASE MAXIMUM ALLOWABLE NUMBER OF WINDOW TINTING MEDICAL
9 EXCEPTION PERMITS
10 SECTION 21. G.S. 20-127(f) reads as rewritten:
11 "(f) Medical Exception. – A person who suffers from a medical condition that causes the
12 person to be photosensitive to visible light may obtain a medical exception permit. To obtain a
13 permit, an applicant shall apply in writing to the Drivers Medical Evaluation Program and have
14 his or her doctor complete the required medical evaluation form provided by the Division. The
15 permit shall be valid for five years from the date of issue, unless a shorter time is directed by the
16 Drivers Medical Evaluation Program. The renewal shall require a medical recertification that the
17 person continues to suffer from a medical condition requiring tinting.
18 A person may receive no more than two four medical exception permits that are valid at any
19 one time. A permit issued under this subsection shall specify the vehicle to which it applies, the
20 windows that may be tinted, and the permitted levels of tinting. The permit shall be carried in the
21 vehicle to which it applies when the vehicle is driven on a highway.
22 The Division shall give a person who receives a medical exception permit a sticker to place
23 on the lower left-hand corner of the rear window of the vehicle to which it applies. The sticker
24 shall be designed to give prospective purchasers of the vehicle notice that the windows of the
25 vehicle do not meet the requirements of G.S. 20-127(b), and shall be placed between the window
26 and the tinting when the tinting is installed. The Division shall adopt rules regarding the
27 specifications of the medical exception sticker. Failure to display the sticker is an infraction
28 punishable by a two hundred dollar ($200.00) fine."
29
